A Case Study: Wealth, Inequality, and the Federal ReserveObviously, if you inherit wealth in this country, you’re instantly ahead of the game.
None of this should have been surprising, since much of the excess money went straight to big banks, rich investors, and speculators.
The net result: an acute post-financial-crisis increase in wealth inequality—on top of the income inequality that was global but especially true in the United States.
According to academic findings, income inequality is, in the most literal sense, making Americans sick.
In sum, the rich are only getting richer and it’s happening at a historic rate.